	OjB4COsPbY [label=<
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="green" WIDTH="150"><B>Rule</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">To constitute a tax free reorganization<BR ALIGN='left'/>under Section 112(g) (1) (D) of the Code<BR ALIGN='left'/>it was not necessary that the persons<BR ALIGN='left'/>who owned the stock of the transferee<BR ALIGN='left'/>corporation should also have owned 80<BR ALIGN='left'/>per cent of the stock of the transferor<BR ALIGN='left'/>corporation. In Toklan Royalty Corp. v.<BR ALIGN='left'/>Jones, D.C., 58 F. Supp. 967, the court<BR ALIGN='left'/>held that there was a tax free<BR ALIGN='left'/>reorganization where persons owning less<BR ALIGN='left'/>than 80 per cent of the stock of the<BR ALIGN='left'/>original corporation owned all of the<BR ALIGN='left'/>stock in the successor corporation.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
>]
